0. Introduction

In this computing practical, you will access multiple resources online to draw inferences on ecological processes at the regional and global levels. Namely, you will access the following online repositories to obtain information: - COMADRE Matrix Animal Database: an open-access repository of animal demographic information. - IUCN Redlist: dataset of conservation status of animals, plants, and fungi - The open tree of life: A repository to pull phylogenetic trees

The following sections walk you through how to access, download, and manipulate the information step by step:

1. Accessing demographic data:

COMADRE is a database of matrix population models (MPMs, hereafter) for animal species. This open-access repository can be further investigated here: https://compadre-db.org, where you will also find information about the demography of plants (COMPADRE). COMADRE currently contains 3,488 MPMs from 415 studies across 429 animal species.

In your lectures in years 2, you were introduced to MPMs, and have more recently examined their transient behaviour in an ecology resilience context. From those lectures, you may remember that MPMs describe the dynamics of a given population in discrete time (e.g.Â last year, this year; a week ago vs.Â today; 12h ago vs.Â now). MPMs explicitly consider how key demographic processes, such as survival and reproduction (a.k.a. âvital ratesâ), change among individuals in the studied population as a function of key properties of individuals in it. Specifically, these models examine how individual heterogeneity relates to the values of these vital rates by studying the role that one (or more) individual-level characteristics (a.k.a. âstatesâ) has/have on the vital rates. In MPMs, individuals in the population are typically classified by age (e.g.Â 0, 1, 2 years old), developmental stage (e.g.Â juvenile, adult, senescent), and/or size ranges (e.g.Â short, medium, tall).

#Clear the R environment
rm(list = ls())

COMADRE contains the key MPM information as well as plenty of metadata. To explore what the names of the metadata mean, please consult with: https://jonesor.github.io/CompadreGuides/user-guide.html). Briefly, the metadata contains information relating to: - Full taxonomy of the studied species (e.g., Kingdom, Phylum, Class,â¦, accepted Latin name, common name) - Original source (e.g.Â year of publication, journal name, authors) - Details of the study (e.g.Â start and end year, criteria used to construct the MPM, GPS coordinates of the population, etc.)

comadre1 <- subset(comadre,
                   # Consider only mammals

                   # studied under "control" (i.e. no treatment) conditions

There is a bit of more fine-tuning we need to do before we can calculate demographic properties from these MPMs. We will use the function cdb_flag() to add columns to the database flagging potential issues with these MPMs, such as missing values, or MPMs that donât meet assumptions necessary to calculate population growth rates (like ergodicity, irreducibility, or primitivity - you can read more on that here: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/j.1461-0248.2011.01659.x).

comadre_flags <- cdb_flag(comadre1)

#We will only be able to calculate population growth rates from matrices 
#that donât contain missing values, and we only want to use matrices that 
#meet the assumption of ergodicity, so weâll subset the database accordingly.
comadre_sub <- subset(comadre_flags,
                      check_NA_A == FALSE &
                      check_ergodic == TRUE)

#Check size of subset data again:
dim(comadre_sub)
## [1] 247  73

Now that you have subset the data to narrow-down your research to mammals, you may want to take a look at some MPMs in the data. Whenever possible, the MPM of a species, examined at a given location, interval, and under a given kind of experimental manipulation (e.g.Â control, fire, hunting, etc.) has been split by the COM(P)ADRE team into its constituent submatrices, such that the matrix A, is the summation of the submatrices that describe processes that depend on survival (submatrix U), on sexual reproduction (F), and clonality (C). Note that when a given animal does not reproduce clonally, C is a matrix of zeros.

Now we are going to obtain some key properties from these MPM. Namely, we will estimate population growth rate and generation time. As you may remember from lecture, the population growth rate (\(\lambda\)) corresponds to the dominant eigenvalue of the MPM A, and it projects the rate of growth (if \(\lambda\) > 1) or decline (\(\lambda\) < 1) of the population. One of the three definitions of generation time (T) is the mean age of reproductive individuals in the population. This life history trait is tightly linked to the rate of population turnover, and it is frequently used in assessments of vulnerability of the IUCN (e.g. https://besjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/1365-2664.13368).

#Obtain population growth rates using the function 
#"lambda" from the R package "popbio
#install.packages("popbio")
library("popbio")

#Using lapply (which applies a function to every element in a list), 
#we will calculate the population growth rate (lambda) for each matrix
comadre_sub$lambda <- unlist(lapply(matA(comadre_sub), popbio::lambda))

#Examine the distribution of population growth rates:
hist(comadre_sub$lambda, xlab= "Population growth rate", main = NULL)
abline(v = 1, col = 'red', lty = 2, lwd = 2)

#To calculate generation time, we will use the R package "Rage"
#install.packages("Rage")
library("Rage")

#Again using lapply, we will now use the U and F matrices 
#to calculate the generation time - look at the function to 
#see the equation here
comadre_sub$gen_T <- mapply(Rage::gen_time, matU(comadre_sub), matF(comadre_sub))

#In the code above, the accessor function matA() is used to extract a list 
#of projection matrices (the full matrix, matA) from every row of comadre_sub. 
#There are also accessor functions for the matrix subcomponents (matU(), 
#matF(), matC()), and for many other parts of the database too.

#Examine the distribution of generation times:
hist(comadre_sub$gen_T, xlab = "Generation time (years)", main = NULL)

#To plot population growth rate and generation time in the phylogeny (Section 3, below), we must have data of these variables that is numeric (e.g. no NAs, no Inf), so we need to eliminate rows with such values:
if (length(which(is.na(comadre_sub$lambda)))>0) {
  comadre_sub <- comadre_sub[-which(is.na(comadre_sub$lambda)),]
}

if (length(which(is.na(comadre_sub$gen_T)))>0) {
  comadre_sub <- comadre_sub[-which(is.na(comadre_sub$gen_T)),]
}

if (length(which(is.infinite(comadre_sub$gen_T)))>0) {
  comadre_sub <- comadre_sub[-which(is.infinite(comadre_sub$gen_T)),]
}

Note that the object âcomadre_subâ contains quite a few MPMs for each species. Sometimes these MPMs correspond to different years (e.g., 2000 to 2001, 2001, to 2002â¦) within the same population, and sometimes they may refer to different populations, or even come from different publications/research groups. As such, for the purposes of todayâs exercise, and in the interest of time, we will only sample one MPM per species:

2. Accessing IUCN Red list status data:

Established in 1964, the International Union for Conservation of Natureâs Red List of Threatened Species has evolved to become the worldâs most comprehensive information source on the global conservation status of animal, fungi and plant species. The IUCN Red List is a critical indicator of the health of the worldâs biodiversity. Far more than a list of species and their status, it is a powerful tool to inform and catalyze action for biodiversity conservation and policy change, critical to protecting the natural resources we need to survive. It provides information about range, population size, habitat and ecology, use and/or trade, threats, and conservation actions that will help inform necessary conservation decisions.

To access the API (Application Programming Interface) of the IUCN, you might want to apply for a token, which can take a few days, or simply use the one I am providing you below. Do please feel free to apply for your own token if you would like - to do so by following these steps: https://apiv3.iucnredlist.org. Watch details here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4T6GXtptmj4

However, to expedite this step, I have accessed and downloaded the data already:

#Install and call the R package 
#install.packages("taxize")
library(taxize)

#This is the token that I obtained from the steps detailed above. It is entirely possible that the API of the IUCN will reject so many requests from independent computers using the same token... so be patient!

#https:/apiv3.iucnredlist.org', provide IUCN access

With these data, we want to do some wrangling. This will be the case almost every time you access data online. Here, we just want information on the IUCN redlist status of each of our unique mammal species, of which there are 37. Then we will bind this information back on to the comadre data.

library(tidyverse)

comadre_iucn <- comadre_sub %>%
  left_join(x = ., y = IUCN_data, by = "SpeciesAccepted") %>% 
  mutate(IUCNstatus = case_when(
    IUCNstatus == "EN" ~ "Endangered",
    IUCNstatus == "VU" ~ "Vulnerable",
    IUCNstatus == "NT" ~ "Near Threatened",
    IUCNstatus == "LC" ~ "Least Concern",
    is.na(IUCNstatus) == TRUE ~ "Not Assessed"),
    IUCNstatus = factor(IUCNstatus, 
                        levels = c("Endangered","Vulnerable",
                                   "Near Threatened","Least Concern",
                                   "Not Assessed")))

dim(comadre_iucn)
## [1] 37 77
dim(comadre_iucn)
## [1] 37 77
#We are going to flatten out this object into a simple data.frame
comadre_iucn <- as.data.frame(comadre_iucn) 

#Adding colours to the IUCN categories
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour <- NA
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour[which(comadre_iucn$IUCNstatus == "Endangered")] <- "Orange" 
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour[which(comadre_iucn$IUCNstatus == "Vulnerable")] <- "Yellow"
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour[which(comadre_iucn$IUCNstatus == "Near Threatened")] <- "Dark green"
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour[which(comadre_iucn$IUCNstatus == "Least Concern")] <- "Green"
comadre_iucn$iucn_colour[which(comadre_iucn$IUCNstatus == "Not Assessed")] <- "Blue"

Now explore both visually and statistically the relationships between generation time, on the one hand, and population growth rate, on the other, with IUCN status of mammals in COMADRE:

3. Phylogenetic tree and phylogenetic analyses

The Open Tree of Life is an open-access online repository that offers phylogenetic information across the most comprehensive group of species across the Tree of Life. Further information can be found here https://tree.opentreeoflife.org/opentree/argus/opentree13.4@ott93302 and here https://besjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/2041-210X.12593.

The first step is to run a taxonomic check on your species names, in case these are not taxonomically accepted (âup to dateâ according the latest biological evidence regarding species relationships)

#Once again, state your species names
my_taxa <- comadre_iucn$SpeciesAccepted

#Use the command 'tnrs_match_names' to run my_taxa through the API of ROTL to check species names
resolved_names <- rotl::tnrs_match_names(names = my_taxa)

Now letâs try to do something more interesting. Let us map the values of IUCN status, population growth rate, and generation time along the phylogeny to examine potential patterns of phylogenetic association. For that, the tree we obtained from OTL will not work because the branches are not dated. That is, the tree holds the structure, but has no information about the time since emergence between sister clades. Instead, we will turn to a tree that I have prepared for you that does have that information

#We will be using the R package phytools
#install.packages("phytools")

#setwd("...")
tree <- read.tree("COMPADRE-COMADRE_Phylo_June_16_2019.tre")

#This tree contains information for most of the species in COMADRE and COMPADRE, and can also be found here https://github.com/jonesor/compadreDB/tree/master/ under the subfolder "Phylogeny" 
plot(tree)

#Let's clean up the names in the tree, so we can compare them with the names in our object
tree$tip.label <- gsub("_", " ", tree$tip.label)

#Now we need to "prune" the tree, which means to cut out the branches that are not present in our data:
pruned_tree <- drop.tip(tree, setdiff(tree$tip.label, comadre_iucn$OTL_unique_name))

# Let us now plot the values of population growth rate at the tips of the phylogeny, and reconstruct the ancestral state of the originating lineange
log_lambdas <- log(setNames(comadre_iucn$lambda, rownames(comadre_iucn)))

# create "contMap" object, which allows for the reconstruction of likely ancestral traits
#my_tree2<-di2multi(pruned.tree)

mammal_contMap_lambda <- contMap(pruned_tree, log_lambdas,plot=FALSE,res=200)
mammal_contMap_lambda <- setMap(mammal_contMap_lambda, c("white","#FFFFB2","#FECC5C","#FD8D3C","#E31A1C"))
plot(mammal_contMap_lambda, fsize=c(0.7,0.8), leg.txt="log(population growth rate)")

par(mar=c(5.1,4.1,4.1,2.1)) ## reset margins to default

#Let's do the same thing for generation time
log_gen_T <- log(setNames(comadre_iucn$gen_T, rownames(comadre_iucn)))
mammal_contMap_gen_T <- contMap(pruned_tree, log_gen_T,plot=FALSE,res=200)
mammal_contMap_gent_T <- setMap(mammal_contMap_gen_T, c("white","light blue","blue","violet","purple"))
plot(mammal_contMap_gent_T, fsize=c(0.7,0.8), leg.txt="log(generation time) (years)")
